  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the best books available to learn SQL?",
  "response": "Learning SQL can be a highly rewarding experience, and there are several excellent books available that cater to different levels of proficiency, from beginners to advanced users. Here are some of the best books to learn SQL:\n\n1. **\"Learning SQL\" by Alan Beaulieu** - This is an excellent book for beginners. It introduces the basics of SQL in a very easy-to-understand manner and covers a wide range of topics with practical examples.\n\n2. **\"SQL in 10 Minutes, Sams Teach Yourself\" by Ben Forta** - A great book for those who want a quick introduction to SQL. Each lesson is designed to be completed in about 10 minutes, making it perfect for busy learners.\n\n3. **\"SQL for Data Analytics\" by Upom Malik, Matt Goldwasser, and Benjamin Johnston** - This book is tailored for those who want to use SQL for data analysis. It includes practical exercises and real-world examples to help you understand how SQL can be used to analyze data.\n\n4. **\"SQL Queries for Mere Mortals: A Hands-On Guide to Data Manipulation in SQL\" by John L. Viescas and Michael J. Hernandez** - This is a comprehensive guide that is suitable for both beginners and intermediate users. It focuses on teaching you how to write effective SQL queries with lots of practical exercises.\n\n5. **\"SQL Cookbook\" by Anthony Molinaro** - If you already have some knowledge of SQL and want to learn advanced techniques, this book is highly recommended. It provides solutions to common problems and includes a wide range of practical recipes.\n\n6. **\"Murach's SQL Server 2019 for Developers\" by Joel Murach** - This book is ideal for developers who want to learn SQL for Microsoft SQL Server. It covers the fundamentals as well as advanced topics that are specifically related to SQL Server.\n\n7. **\"Head First SQL: Your Brain on SQL -- A Learner's Guide\" by Lynn Beighley** - This book is designed in a very engaging and interactive style, making it great for those who prefer a more visual and hands-on approach to learning.\n\n8. **\"Effective SQL: 61 Specific Ways to Write Better SQL\" by John L. Viescas and Douglas J. Steele** - This book is full of expert advice and tips on how to write more efficient and effective SQL queries. Perfect for intermediate to advanced users.\n\nThese books offer a range of approaches and depth, so you can choose the one that best fits your current skill level and learning style.",
